    <!-- Quantified Impact -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <h2 class="mb-4 text-center">📊 A transition you can measure</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          Compared with the traditional AZERTY, AZERTY Global moves only <strong>8.3% of characters</strong>,
          which affects <strong>less than 1% of real-world keystrokes</strong> (character-frequency analysis
          on a French reference corpus). If you already type on AZERTY, the switch takes hours, not weeks.
        </p>

        <p class="text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          Coming from a US layout is a bigger step — you are relearning the letter positions of the
          keyboard France actually uses. But it is a one-time investment that pays off on every French
          computer you will ever touch.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Why AZERTY Global rather than US International -->
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container container--narrow">
        <h2 class="section__title text-center">💡 Why AZERTY Global rather than the US International QWERTY?</h2>

        <p class="mb-4 section-lead">
          The US International layout is the go-to answer for English speakers who need é and ñ. It works — until you write French for real.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4 text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          On US International, <strong>every apostrophe costs an extra keystroke</strong>: ' is a dead key,
          so <em>don't</em> and <em>it's</em> require ' + space, dozens of times a day. French pushes it
          further: no œ ligature at all (<em>cœur</em>, <em>sœur</em>, <em>œuvre</em>), and the French
          quotation marks « » hide behind shortcuts almost nobody knows.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4 text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          Then there is the hardware: <strong>keyboards in France are physically AZERTY</strong> — your
          office computer, shared machines, your French laptop. Running US International means the printed
          keycaps lie to you on every one of them.
        </p>

        <p class="text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          AZERTY Global keeps the AZERTY base France uses and fixes its real flaws: accented capitals with
          <kbd>Caps Lock</kbd>, programming symbols on the home row, a direct period — plus dead-key accents
          for Spanish, German, Portuguese, Polish and 200+ other languages.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Vision / Manifesto -->
